  "prompt": "What is the formula used to calculate thermal energy and how is it calculated?",
  "response": "The formula for calculating thermal energy is:\n\nQ = m \u00d7 c \u00d7 \u0394T\n\nWhere:\nQ = Thermal energy (heat transferred)\nm = Mass of the substance\nc = Specific heat capacity of the substance\n\u0394T = Change in temperature (final temperature - initial temperature)\n\nTo calculate thermal energy:\n1. Determine the mass of the substance\n2. Know the specific heat capacity of the material\n3. Calculate the temperature change\n4. Multiply these three values together\n\nExample:\nIf 2 kg of water increases from 20\u00b0C to 80\u00b0C, with water's specific heat capacity of 4,186 J/(kg\u00b7\u00b0C):\nQ = 2 kg \u00d7 4,186 J/(kg\u00b7\u00b0C) \u00d7 (80\u00b0C - 20\u00b0C)\nQ = 2 \u00d7 4,186 \u00d7 60\nQ = 501,120 J or 501.12 kJ of thermal energy\n\nThe units of thermal energy are typically joules (J) or kilojoules (kJ).",
